  <h2 id="known-unknowns">What GhanaWorld Still Does Not Know</h2>

  <p>Honest uncertainty is a requirement, not an admission of weakness. The following gaps remain in GhanaWorld's diaspora analysis:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Success case data:</strong> GhanaWorld has documented 33 diaspora lessons and 35 failure patterns but has not yet completed analysis of a verified diaspora success case with operating data (not press releases). The success case placeholder remains open. Until it is filled, the analysis skews toward what fails because that is where the evidence is strongest.</li>
    <li><strong>Post-IMF diaspora investment behaviour:</strong> How diaspora capital flows will respond to the IMF exit window (August 2026) is modelled but unobserved. Historical patterns from previous program completions suggest a 12 to 18 month investment surge, but the current political and legislative environment (Diaspora Participation Bill, GIPC reform) has no precedent.</li>
    <li><strong>Digital product revenue validation:</strong> The portfolio products (GhanaScope, DiasporaDesk, GrantPilot, AfriDiligence) have been designed and stress-tested within GhanaWorld's simulation framework. Real-world revenue data will either confirm or revise the 7.20/10 Digital Services sector score.</li>
    <li><strong>Manager market evolution:</strong> FP-010 documents manager scarcity as a structural constraint. Whether the growing diaspora investment wave will create a professional local-manager class (as India's IT industry created a professional services management class) is an open question.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>These unknowns do not invalidate the analysis. They define its boundaries. GhanaWorld will update this guide as new evidence emerges.</p>

